1. AESGCM.generate_key(bit_length=256): This command requests 32 cryptographically secure random bytes (32 * 8 = 256 bits) from the operating system's underlying entropy 
pool (os.urandom). This key acts as the un-guessable master lock.

2. File I/O ("wb" and "rb"): Notice that the key and encrypted files are handled using wb (Write Binary) and rb (Read Binary) modes. Because keys and encrypted payloads are 
raw arbitrary bytes—not plain ASCII text.

3. os.urandom(12): Generates a Nonce (Number used Once) exactly 12 bytes long. In GCM mode, never encrypt two different files with the same key and same nonce, or the 
mathematical defenses collapse.

4. aesgcm.encrypt(nonce, data, None): The core encryption math. It takes the nonce and your raw file bytes, processes it through the AES algorithm, and appends a 16-byte 
Authentication Tag to the very end of the output ciphertext.

5. file_contents[:12] (Slicing): Because the nonce is required to decrypt the file, the application glues the 12-byte nonce directly to the front of the encrypted file 
during encryption.

6. aesgcm.decrypt(nonce, actual_encrypted_data, None): This doesn't just decrypt; it performs a cryptographic integrity check using the appended 16-byte authentication tag.
If a malicious actor changes even a single bit of the file while it's stored on disk, the tag validation will fail completely.
Python will instantly trigger a InvalidTag exception and refuse to spit out any decrypted data, keeping the user completely safe from tampered data injections.
